To secure an AWS VPC using IAM policies, you can use condition keys such as `ec2:Vpc` to specify that actions can only be performed on security groups in a specific VPC. For example:

```
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "AllowAddRemoveRulesForSpecificVPC",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": ["ec2:AuthorizeSecurityGroupIngress", "ec2:ReauthorizeSecurityGroupIngress"],
      "Resource": "*",
      "Condition": {
        "StringLike": {
          "ec2:Vpc": "arn:aws:ec2:region:account-id:vpc/vpc-ec43eb89"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

[Source: aws/EC2/Policy structure<a name="iam-policy-structure"></a> > Condition keys for Amazon EC2<a name="amazon-ec2-keys"></a>]

Additionally, you can use IAM policies to control access to AWS resources based on tags. For example:

```
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "AllowAccessToResourcesWithTagKeyAndValue",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": "*",
      "Resource": "*",
      "Condition": {
        "StringEquals": {
          "aws:ResourceTag/Environment": "dev"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

[Source: aws/ECS/Identity\-based policy examples for Amazon Elastic Container Service<a name="security_iam_id-based-policy-examples"></a> > Policy best practices<a name="security_iam_service-with-iam-policy-best-practices"></a>]

It's also recommended to use AWS managed policies and move towards least-privilege permissions, as well as apply conditions in IAM policies to further restrict access. [Source: aws/ECS/Identity\-based policy examples for Amazon Elastic Container Service<a name="security_iam_id-based-policy-examples"></a> > Policy best practices<a name="security_iam_service-with-iam-policy-best-practices"></a>]
